commentBody:
@John 

I was surprised (maybe) see that the first known use of MEET-CUTE was in 1952.

I say “maybe” because I have a vague memory of having looked this up before in connection with a previous puzzle.

@Marcia 

😂😂😂

You win the internet today!

@Times Rita 

Great story!

And I've been studying Italian, so thank you for adding "pazza" to my vocabulary, lol!

@EAV 
I must compliment you for being so gracious.  That is such a beautiful quality and we certainly could use more of that nowadays. I hope to see one of your puzzles here one day.  
Have a great puzzle-solving week to all.

@Andrzej
Doesn't English drive you crazy?  We hav a herd of cows or a herd of goats.  But a herd of elk or deer or cattle.

And then there are those of us who insist the plural of moose is meese, because plural of goose is geese, right?

@Kate 
FWIW, only one guard (and the only guy under 6’11”) has achieved this, Alvin Robertson in 1986, and he is the only one of the four guys who had steals among his four doubles. Also, prior to 1973-74 the NBA did not officially track blocks and steals.  Unofficially (as tallied by a Philly sportswriter), 76er Wilt Chamberlain had a 1968 game against the Lakers with a quintuple-double with 53 pts, 32 rebs, 24 blocks,  14 assts, and 11 steals. All of the four officially recorded quadruple doubles occurred between 1974 and 1994, but there has been a lot of talk about Victor Wembanyama being the next likely one to do this . See:

<a href="https://tinyurl.com/bdbzbe8a" target="_blank">https://tinyurl.com/bdbzbe8a</a>

@Helen Wright 

I have different severe allergies (the buzz of an insect can make me duck and run instantly)...but even so I can admire bees (and reminisce about my beekeeping apprenticeship with my grand-dad)...
          So I am sorry you don't see the beauty and charm of cats and kittens.  Charlotte the Kitty joins me in shaking our heads sadly at this thought.

@Mean Old Lady 
I mean no disrespect to Miss Charlotte, who I’m sure is a delight. Sadly my experience with her kin has not been great; I swear they know I’m not a fan and always make a beeline for me, rubbing around my legs etc etc. I can certainly admire the sleek beauty of cat kind, but only as long as we don’t breathe the same air. I’ve been hospitalised/ventilated too many times for me to ever be comfortable in their, albeit gorgeous, presence.
 I’m the same with horses, so naturally my daughter was horse mad. Many a drive home from a hack has seen me driving with my head out of the window, while she is wearing as little as decently possible; the hair covered riding gear in a sealed box in the boot. The things we do for our kids.

@Cathy Parrish,

Congratulations! That is a remarkable streak!

I hope your son continues to do well. How fortunate he is to have your support.

@Barry Ancona 
*shiver* A New Yorker Monday by Natan Last is always a workout.

I would go so far as to say that in general, a Monday New Yorker puzzle is harder than a Saturday NYT. I realize that may be seen as heresy by some.

@Barry Ancona 

I zipped through most of Natan Last’s grid, but I am stuck in the NW. A  runner I’ve never heard of next to a character from a show I’ve never seen, crossing a comedian whose name I have yet to recognize . . . . It’s a lot to try and figure out from letter patterns. 

I agree that, ever since the New Yorker went from five full-sized puzzles a week to three, the overall trend has been that they are easier than they were.

@suejean 

It did strike me as rather US-centric as I solved, so I am not surprised you found it difficult. But at least it included your London subway.

See ya tomorrow!

@Linda Jo ,

I appreciate your kindness in giving me an excuse,  but in fact I spent my first 40 years in the USA, so should do better.  I’ve been here for 47 years . 

Until tomorrow.

@Grant 

It's not the default in Europe. One has to specifically request water and specify whether still or sparkling. And usually ask for a preferred brand.


Do emus like Evian? Eau de emu.

@Grant 

I don't know about NY but think it would only be mentioned if you eat with people who are glass-bottled water fans. But then again they might just ask for Perrier etc. So it's understandable that the clue was weird to you.

p.s. Is asking for water the same as ordering water???

@Emmett 

Well, both elk and elks are the plural of elk.  Just Google "plural of elk" You get: elk /ˈɛlk/ noun. plural elk or elks.

